HEADWORD: Influent
<hw>In"flu*ent</hw> <pr>(⟦icr⟧n"fl⟦usl⟧*⟦eit⟧nt)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos>
<ety>[L. <ets>influens</ets>, <ets>-entis</ets>, p. pr. of
<ets>influere</ets>, <ets>influxum</ets>, to flow in; pref.
<ets>in-</ets> in + <ets>fluere</ets> to flow. See
<er>Fluid</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Flowing in.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧With
<xex>influent</xex> tide.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Cowper.</au>
⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Influent</xex> odors.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Mrs. Browning.</au>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Exerting influence; influential.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I find no office by name assigned unto Dr. Cox, who was virtually
<qex>influent</qex> upon all, and most active.</q>
<rj><qau>Fuller.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Influential</ent>⟦br⟧
